White House Press Secretary Robert Gibbs held a press briefing on June 17, 2009. He addressed various topics including the situation in Iran, same-sex benefits, the firing of Inspector General Walpin, healthcare reform, and North Korea. Gibbs also discussed the President's commitment to repealing the Defense of Marriage Act (DOMA) and "don't ask, don't tell." He mentioned that the President supports a change in the law that would allow federal employees to receive more substantial medical benefits or retirement benefits, and that the President is working with members of Congress and the Pentagon to repeal "don't ask, don't tell." Gibbs also mentioned that the President's message for Father's Day would focus on the responsibilities of fathers.